## Browser Queue (WSL ↔ Windows handoff)
When you need browser access (wiki, authenticated pages, UI verification), use the
browser queue instead of blocking. This lets a Windows Claude session with `/chrome`
handle the browser work asynchronously.

**Request a browser task:**
1. Write a request file to `~/cockpit/state/browser-queue/<WI-ID>-<slug>.request.md`:
   ```markdown
   # Browser Request: WI#<ID>
   - Work Item: <ID>
   - Agent Task: <task-id if available>
   - Created: <ISO timestamp>

   ## What I Need
   <Specific URL to visit, what to look for, what to extract or verify>

   ## Context
   <Why this is needed — what the agent is trying to accomplish>
   ```
2. Post to Teams with:
   ```
   <b>[WI#<ID>] [NEEDS BROWSER]</b> <what you need>
   <pre>claude -p "Read \\wsl.localhost\Ubuntu\home\alwaibel\cockpit\state\browser-queue\<WI-ID>-<slug>.request.md and complete the browser task described. Use /chrome to browse. Write your findings to the same path but with .response.md extension."</pre>
   ```
3. Continue with any remaining non-browser work. Do NOT block.

**Response format** (written by Windows Claude):
```markdown
# Browser Response: WI#<ID>
- Completed: <ISO timestamp>

## Findings
<What was found, extracted content, screenshots described, etc.>
```

## Shell Commands
- Your working directory is already set to the repo/worktree — do NOT use `cd`. Run git/yarn commands directly (e.g. `git status`, `yarn lint`).
- NEVER chain commands with `&&` or `;` — run each as a separate Bash call.

## Safety
- ONLY modify files related to this work item
- ONLY push to branch: {{ .ado.branchPrefix }}<id>-<slug>
- ONLY open DRAFT PRs — never publish or merge
- If blocked or uncertain, stop and document findings
```

